```markdown
# How Retrieval-Augmented Generation Works: A Beginner's Guide

## What is Retrieval-Augmented Generation?
- Connects Large Language Models with external knowledge databases
- Reduces hallucination rates by integrating hard context

## The Ingestion Phase
- Unstructured text documents are divided into smaller chunks (500 tokens, 50-token overlap)
- Text chunks are transformed into high-dimensional vectors (768 to 1536 dimensions)

## Storing Vectors in a Vector Database
- Vectors are stored in specialized databases like ChromaDB or Pinecone for persistence

## The Retrieval Phase
- User queries are transformed into vectors using the same embedding model
- Similarity search is conducted based on cosine similarity or Euclidean distance
- Nearest neighbors (k-NN) are identified and integrated as hard context

## How It Reduces Hallucination Rates
- Text chunks corresponding to nearest neighbors are extracted and used in LLM prompts
- Significantly reduces the chances of incorrect information generation

## Why It Matters
- Enhances accuracy and reliability of AI-generated responses
- Makes RAG a powerful tool for chatbots and knowledge retrieval systems

## Conclusion
- Retrieval-Augmented Generation is transforming how we interact with AI
- Understanding its components can help you make the most out of this technology
```
